    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  Prone position ventilation has been shown to decrease mortality and improve oxygenation in ARDS patients. With best of our knowledge, no study reported physiological effect of prone position in SARS-CoV-2 infected ARDS patients. In this prospective observational study, data of n=20 consecutive laboratory confirmed SARS-CoV-2 patients with severe ARDS as per Berlin definition was included. Data of 20 patients analyzed with a median (Interquartile range, IQR) age of 56 (45.5-67) y and median (IQR) P/F ratio of 56 (54-66) with a median (IQR) PEEP of 12 (12-14) before initiation of prone position. Seventy-five percentage (95% CI 53.1-88.8) patients were prone responders at 16h prone session and 50 (95% CI 29.9-70.1) % patients were sustained responders. There was a significant decrease in plateau airway pressure (p&lt;0.0001), peak airway pressure (p&lt;0.0001) and driving pressure(p&lt;0.0001) and increase in static compliance (p=0.001), P/F ratio (p&lt;0.0001), PaO\n                  <jats:sub>2</jats:sub>\n                  (p=0.0002)and SpO\n                  <jats:sub>2</jats:sub>\n                  (p=0.0004) at 4h and 16h since initiation of prone session and also after return of supine position. Prone position in SARS-CoV-2 infected severe ARDS patients is associated with improvement in lung compliance and oxygenation in two-third of the patients and persisted in half of the patients.\n                </jats:p>",
